9) What are destructors in C++? How is it handled in Java?
-->In C++, a destructor is a special member function used to perform cleanup operations and deallocate resources when an object is destroyed.
        Java, by contrast, uses automatic garbage collection for memory management and does not have an explicit destructor function like C++

10) How is multiple inheritance handled in Java?
-->Java does not support multiple inheritance of classes directly. This design choice was made to avoid complexity and ambiguity issues, most notably the "diamond problem".
    However, multiple inheritance of behavior can be achieved in two primary ways: through interfaces and composition.


11) What is the difference between structures in C and classes in Java?
-->Structures in C are purely used for grouping data, while classes in Java are the fundamental building blocks of object-oriented programming (OOP),
    combining both data and behavior into a single blueprint

12) Why does Java not support operator overloading?
-->Java does not support user-defined operator overloading as a deliberate design decision to prioritize simplicity, readability, and consistency in the language. 

13) Compare access specifiers in C++ and Java.
-->Core Differences
    Number of Specifiers/Modifiers: C++ has three primary access specifiers (public, private, protected). 
    Java has four access modifiers: public, private, protected, and a default (package-private) modifier which uses no keyword.

14) What is the difference in memory management between C++ and Java?
-->The primary difference is that C++ uses manual memory management, requiring the programmer to explicitly allocate and deallocate memory,\
    while Java uses automatic memory management through a garbage collector

15) Can you directly manage memory in Java like in C/C++?
-->No, you cannot directly manage memory in Java.

